# Literature Review

## Introduction

Insurance pricing for risks associated with information technology systems is a complex challenge that
requires integrating the disciplines of operations management, security, and economics. This literature
review aims to explore the existing research findings related to the development of a socioeconomic
modelling framework for cyber-insurance decisions. The framework encompasses entity relationship
diagrams, security maturity models, and economic models, aiming to address the challenge of capturing
organizational structure in the design and pricing of cyber-insurance policies. Additionally, the review
will highlight knowledge gaps and propose potential future research directions.

## Cyber-Insurance and Pricing

Insurance pricing is typically based on the historical data and experience of insurance companies regarding
the frequency and magnitude of losses in organizations based on factors such as size, industry sector, and
location [^1^]. However, cyber-insurance presents a unique challenge due to limited data history [^1^].
This limitation necessitates the development of innovative modelling frameworks that can accurately
capture the complexities of cyber risks and organizational structures.

## Socioeconomic Modelling Framework

The proposed socioeconomic modelling framework for cyber-insurance decisions combines entity relationship diagrams, security maturity models, and economic models [^1^]. The entity relationship
diagrams provide a visual representation of the relationships and dependencies between entities within an
organization, including IT systems, processes, and stakeholders [^2^]. By incorporating these diagrams
into the modelling framework, it becomes possible to assess the impact of cyber risks on different
components of the organization and develop appropriate insurance policies.
Security maturity models, on the other hand, enable organizations to evaluate and improve their cybersecurity capabilities [^2^]. By including security maturity models in the framework, insurers can assess
the cybersecurity readiness of potential policyholders and adjust insurance premiums accordingly. This
ensures that organizations with higher cybersecurity maturity receive more favorable pricing, encouraging
investments in cybersecurity measures.
