Economic models form an integral part of the socioeconomic modelling framework as they provide the
foundation for pricing cyber-insurance policies [^1^]. These models consider various factors such as
the potential financial losses from cyber incidents, the cost of implementing security measures, and the
market demand for cyber-insurance. By incorporating economic models into the framework, insurers can
calculate accurate premiums that reflect the actual risks and costs associated with cyber risks.

## Integration and Synthesis of Research Findings

Various research findings contribute to the development of the proposed socioeconomic modelling
framework for cyber-insurance decisions. Chetty et al. (2020) emphasize the importance of incorporating
private sector data and experience into economic analyses [^1^]. This finding aligns with the inclusion
of economic models in the framework, which rely on historical data and industry insights to determine
insurance premiums.
Eppinger and Browning (2012) provide insights into the use of design structure matrix methods for
managing complex systems, which can be applied to the development of entity relationship diagrams
within the framework [^2^]. This research finding highlights the need for a comprehensive understanding
of an organization's structure and dependencies to accurately model the impact of cyber risks.
Skelcher and Smith (2014) contribute to the framework by emphasizing the significance of institutional
logics and actor identities in hybrid organizations [^3^]. This insight can be incorporated into the entity
relationship diagrams to capture the different perspectives and motivations of stakeholders within an
organization, thus enabling a more nuanced assessment of cyber risks.
Cole, Stevenson, and Aitken (2019) discuss the implications of blockchain technology for supply chain
management, which can be relevant to the design and pricing of cyber-insurance policies [^4^]. The
integration of blockchain technology into the framework can enhance transparency and trust in insurance
transactions, enabling more accurate pricing and claims settlement processes.

## Knowledge Gaps and Future Research Directions

While the proposed socioeconomic modelling framework for cyber-insurance decisions addresses the
challenge of capturing organizational structure, there are still several knowledge gaps that present
opportunities for future research. First, the framework could benefit from further research on the specific
factors that contribute to the pricing of cyber-insurance policies. This research could explore how different
organizational characteristics, such as industry sector, organizational size, and geographic location, affect
2 / 5
